{
  "answer": "**Allama Iqbal's poem \"Tanhai\" (Solitude)** appears in *Bang-E-Dara Part 2* (1924), his seminal Urdu poetry collection.[^1]\n\nHere's the English translation:\n\n> **Solitude**[^2]  \n>   \n> Are the stars sorrowful in the night?  \n> Are they not your companions![^3]  \n>   \n> This lofty, silent sky so deep,  \n> The slumbering earth, the world asleep.[^4]  \n>   \n> This moon, the desert, vale, and mountain-bar,  \n> All Nature is a wild rose garden, near and far.[^5]  \n>   \n> These lovely pearls, so bright they are,  \n> Are but your tears, become a star.[^6]  \n>   \n> What is this longing you cannot remit, O heart!  \n> For Nature is your kindred spirit, O heart![^7]\n\nThe poem meditates on cosmic companionship amid apparent isolation, portraying nature as a vast, living garden that mirrors the heart's yearnings.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 25 (/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25/translation/).\n[^2]: /works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25/translation/#p-125bb6\n[^3]: /works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25/translation/#p-e79836\n[^4]: /works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25/translation/#p-0ef4d8\n[^5]: /works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25/translation/#p-471a1d\n[^6]: /works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25/translation/#p-36f218\n[^7]: /works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/25/translation/#p-8846ae",
